 the view over the canal create a scene that feels almost cinematic. In the evening, with the soft lights reflecting on the water, it becomes even more magical.\n\nA short stop, but a memorable one. The Bridge of Sighs is a must-see if you want to feel the true spirit of Venice.','2025-11-20 19:18:18','Google','2025-12-15 18:54:23'),(227,273,'Christopher B','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/102107706244720620549/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocKwnJ8lgfjOeZ0IrFyAkifLShJ0yrAwdYvAUjMiRvWrjv8J6w=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba4',5,'Take the tour inside and you can walk though it.  Unbelievable history there.  Picture is view from inside it looking out. Great pictures from bridge down near the water.  Venice is so beautiful and a great place to spend time at.  Take a gondola ride under the bridge of signs. So many things to see and do in Venice.   Definitely take some tours and learn the history of the city.  It is so worth it.','2025-08-29 01:54:39','Google','2025-12-15 18:54:23'),(228,273,'Yuliia Lapushanska','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/105022415200227015092/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjXM71_Lf2D6R--x01wGZF5FwEK3B84ZRkGLJkoxOmunAx9BqSIL=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba6',5,'A bridge of sighs — and a reminder of the One who hears every cry.\n\nThe Bridge of Sighs in Venice carries a heavy history. It once connected the courtrooms to the prison — a final passage for those who had been judged, their sighs echoing through the stone as they glimpsed their last view of freedom.\n\nBut even in a place of sorrow, there is hope.\nBecause there is One who hears every sigh, sees every tear, and offers true freedom — not just from chains, but from sin.\n\n“The Lord is close to the brokenhearted and saves those who are crushed in spirit.” (Psalm 34:18)\n\nThe Bridge of Sighs reminds us that judgment is real — but so is mercy.\nWhere human justice ends, divine grace begins. Through Jesus, the ultimate Judge became our Savior.\nHe took our place so we could walk in freedom, not in fear.\n\nSo even the saddest bridges can become sacred places when they point us to the cross —\nwhere the deepest sigh was breathed, and the greatest love was revealed.\n\nTo God be the glory — even in our sighs, He brings salvation.','2025-07-18 21:20:23','Google','2025-12-15 18:54:23'),(229,273,'Dr P J George','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/108646699983361253328/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocJJ1yrmapAw5-mofvQjv4zwm1t_xgLEw5-ou5cV4wKCxiio7Q=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba6',4,'Famous historical site. It is an enclosed bridge that passes over the Rio di Palazzo. It is made of white limestone and has windows with stone bars. It connects the New Prison to the interrogation rooms in Doge\'s Palace. The English name comes from the suggestion that prisoners would stop on the bridge and sigh at their final view of the beautiful Venice city before being led away to their cells.','2025-10-29 07:40:37','Google','2025-12-15 18:54:23'),(230,273,'Seema','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/104754513962451238088/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocLwffeHSNl4nEMxixtaJ3wqm2wKaPajEHXcriIfYPauxc_x99bK=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba4',5,'Venice stands as a masterpiece of history and romance, with its enchanting canals, stunning architectural marvels, and world-famous attractions like St. Mark’s Basilica and the Rialto Bridge. The gondola rides only add to its charm','2025-06-19 18:46:04','Google','2025-12-15 18:54:23'),(231,274,'Michael Offord','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/118139688509724839965/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjUCYcnQ9p_fF7bpz5p0dlxJtJ-6yRZkgizWzoZieS9pO2nu0Dw=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba6',4,'A lovely old house converted into a museum with ceilings by some of greatest Venetian artists.\n\nUpon entering one is met with a vast painted hall, of sublime quality and design. On the same room are a set of state rooms with art, furniture and other items. I especially enjoyed the tapestries, though they are in need of a clean and some restoration.\n\nThe upper floors are galleries. There is one statue of a veiled lady that is particularly impressive.','2025-10-05 19:01:22','Google','2025-12-15 18:55:56'),(232,274,'Pandaz','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/100303203045051136425/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocJhqPesSoPGarCTd4xafadloRd1ju1AAX8D8bxZX3cAUelAeQ=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba3',5,'Beautiful building right along the Grand Canal, next to a vaporetto stop.\nIt is such a charming place but so underrated!\nYou can enjoy art and culture in peace and quiet - it was not crowded. Or even enjoy some food and drinks with great view in the cafe before the entrance.\nThere\'s also a small garden at the back!','2025-10-07 15:42:01','Google','2025-12-15 18:55:56'),(233,274,'Jerome Adorable','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/107635454349184345931/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjVR8Q0nb7s3EvZuffVdj5RV2uTV4CEtb9j4b4zgZ-qe50oK3LH-Nw=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba5',5,'A must visit Museum. It is truely impressive. The architecture and historical atmosphere make you feel like stepping back in time. The exhibition of  Paintings and artifacts are amazing with \"wow\" moment.  The staffs were friendly and knowledgeable.','2025-08-28 19:31:36','Google','2025-12-15 18:55:56'),(234,274,'Giulia Brioschi','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/102091842272984356359/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjVTjbYRQDW4GQxnMpu32rWeoPr4procHHWyC-2kHeFB2WAsR4vnPA=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba5',4,'Ca’ Rezzonico is a magnificent museum on the Grand Canal that immerses you in the splendor of 18th-century Venice. Lavishly decorated rooms, Murano chandeliers, and masterpieces by Tiepolo and Longhi capture the opulence of the era. It’s a beautifully preserved glimpse into the life of the Venetian aristocracy—elegant, theatrical, and unforgettable.','2025-07-14 14:46:08','Google','2025-12-15 18:55:56'),(235,274,'Seokjin Ham','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/100335057264723274172/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocIhtf6A7X2UDP--Xi1vhwXxfhLJk0GUh_pTYJvgqrBOTATbUg=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba7',5,'A masterpiece of Venetian Baroque and Rococo architecture, the palace now serves as the Museum of 18th-Century Venice (Museo del Settecento Veneziano). It was originally commissioned in 1649 by the noble Bon family and designed by the renowned architect Baldassare Longhena. However, construction was halted due to Longhena’s death and the Bon family’s financial difficulties. In 1751, the palace was acquired by the wealthy Rezzonico family, who completed it in 1758 under the direction of Giorgio Massari. Since 1936, the palace has been open to the public as a museum showcasing the art, culture, and daily life of 18th-century Venetian nobility. Visitors can explore opulently decorated rooms, period furnishings, and works by artists such as Tiepolo and Longhi, offering a vivid glimpse into Venice’s golden age.\n※ Included in the Venice Museum Pass.','2025-06-15 11:58:35','Google','2025-12-15 18:55:56'),(236,275,'Sarah','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/103648188396423667678/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjVWWVw3s2CTpui9CcFQIbAUqOGfOwgas-sm0mR0zLbiY6fTv8--=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba3',5,'I had bought a pass to the Doge\'s Palace which included admission to a bunch of other things including this cute little museum. I probably wouldn\'t have gone otherwise, but it was worth it for a quick stop. You first step inside a small courtyard, which is kinda cool in it\'s own way, and then walk up a set of stairs to three-ish major rooms. The first room you\'ll enter contains historical info and documents on Carlo Goldoni along with theme-appropriate decor, the one to the left has a bunch of old marionettes on display, and the one to the right is set up with more documents and decor. Not everything was translated into English but they did have some things translated, although some were only available via a QR code. The lack of translations on the video playing in a side room was a bit of a downer, but the access to a decent bathroom while out touring that day more than made up for it. I really enjoyed the variety of marionettes and how they were displayed, what a fun room to visit. Go here for a unique little side quest in Venice!','2025-11-26 07:25:28','Google','2025-12-15 18:57:25'),(237,275,'Michael Offord','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/118139688509724839965/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjUCYcnQ9p_fF7bpz5p0dlxJtJ-6yRZkgizWzoZieS9pO2nu0Dw=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba6',4,'A charming but small museum dedicated to the Venetian playwright in his family home, which tells the story of some of his plays and reforms to theatrical performances.\n\nAlso on display some puppets..','2025-10-04 15:15:34','Google','2025-12-15 18:57:25'),(238,275,'CityScrolls','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/111519204745516453895/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjX4OIabw5P96_uY9IICqaQjfXNYRMo7YqyopN2Hr3CeKz4SObk=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba4',5,'While this museum may not impress everyone, if you already have a Venezia Unica City Pass or MUVE Museum Pass, stopping by for a visit is a no-brainer.\n\nInside the elegant palazzo, you\'ll find reconstructions from Goldoni\'s plays, featuring mannequins dressed in authentic 18th-century costumes and surrounded by original furniture and objects from the era. The section on puppet theatre is especially captivating, showcasing original marionettes and the only surviving puppet theatre, once common in the wealthy homes of the time.\n\nWhile indeed all texts are in Italian, with tools like translation apps, understanding the content is a breeze.','2025-02-02 18:19:22','Google','2025-12-15 18:57:25'),(239,275,'Marie Nevludová','https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/105714883307270696367/reviews','https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocLZwN08